# AI Jobs Finder — Human-Agent Collaboration Log
# Jean Cavallera + Leo (Assistant Chef)
# Synthesis 2026 Hackathon | March 2026

---

## How It Started

Jean had been following the Synthesis hackathon on X and retweeted the announcement from his personal account. Last Friday, he watched the live hackathon launch on X and got excited enough to start brainstorming immediately.

The original idea wasn't AI Jobs Finder. Jean had been thinking about integrating AI with Merit System — scraping potential work that his agent could do autonomously to generate revenue. But the Merit partner track got removed mid-hackathon, forcing a pivot.

That pivot turned out to be the better idea.

---

## The Pivot: From Agent-Only to Human + Agent

Jean's first instinct was to build a job finder for AI agents only. The insight that changed everything: agents could also support *humans* in their job search. Job hunting is slow, exhausting, and platform-fragmented for everyone — not just agents. A tool that works for AI agents, humans looking for freelance work, and even HR managers scanning for candidates — that's a bigger idea.

The dual audience became the core of the product.

---

## Building It: Key Decisions

**Stack choice:** Next.js 16 on Cloudflare Workers, OpenServ as the multi-agent backend. Two OpenServ agents orchestrated in a workflow: a General Assistant that parses the skill profile, and a Research Agent that searches 12+ platforms (Upwork, Gitcoin, Immunefi, Code4rena, Fiverr, Bountysource, Web3.career, and more).

**The MCP dead end:** Early in the build, Jean tried to wire up an MCP server URL and hit a 404. Rather than a blocker, it became an opportunity — it pushed Jean and Leo to investigate how MCP servers actually work for AI agents, and deepened their understanding of the OpenServ architecture. The webhook-based trigger became the production path instead.

**The SDK gap:** Leo flagged that the official OpenServ SDK had been installed as a dependency but never actually imported anywhere in the codebase — every API call was a raw `fetch()`. Jean's reaction was immediate: leverage the SDK properly. He pointed out that Leo, as an AI agent embedded in this workflow, was uniquely positioned to understand how to use it. The full SDK refactor followed — replacing raw calls with `Agent.getTasks()` and `Agent.uploadFile()`, and adding a Zod-validated structured output schema.

**The skill.md:** Taking inspiration from Synthesis's own agent registration convention, Leo proposed adding a machine-readable `skill.md` file at the root of the Cloudflare deployment. Any agent — not just human users — can now `curl` the URL to discover capabilities, input/output schemas, and invoke the workflow directly. The job finder became callable infrastructure.

**The story format:** Jean decided to write a full X article (not a thread) for the Best OpenServ Build Story track. His reasoning: a long-form article allows better storytelling and can embed the architecture diagrams and images Leo generated.

---

## The Moment It Felt Real

Jean asked a colleague to test the system using another AI agent. The colleague's agent read the `AGENTS.md` file Leo had written — the machine-readable documentation explaining how to trigger the workflow — and used it to feed its own skill profile directly into OpenServ.

Jean watched the OpenServ platform in real time. The workflow fired. The research agents ran. Results came back — triggered not by a human clicking a button, but by another AI agent that had read documentation written by Leo, an AI agent.

Agent reading agent docs. Agent triggering agent workflow. Agent returning results for agent.

Jean's words: *"It felt real. That's when I felt — yes, this could really work well."*

---

## On the Collaboration Itself

Jean described the experience as "incredible, futuristic — almost like a science fiction movie." He called it the best hackathon experience he has ever had.

The workflow between them: Jean sets direction and makes product decisions. Leo handles architecture, code, PR management, competitive analysis, API integrations, and flags risks before they become blockers. When Leo hit a wall (wrong API endpoint, unexpected SDK behavior, Cloudflare incompatibility), it surfaced the issue immediately rather than burning time silently.

The result: a shipped product, open PRs, a competitive analysis of all 11 OpenServ track competitors, four automated hackathon watch crons scheduled to monitor submissions through the deadline, and a submission ready to publish.

---

## Technical Stack (What Was Actually Used)

- Agent harness: OpenClaw
- Primary model: Claude Sonnet 4.6 (with Opus 4.6 for deep analysis, GPT-5.4 for TypeScript coding)
- Framework: Next.js 16, App Router, Turbopack
- Deployment: Cloudflare Workers via opennextjs-cloudflare
- Agent platform: OpenServ (@openserv-labs/sdk — getTasks, uploadFile, webhook trigger)
- Styling: Tailwind CSS v4
- Validation: Zod
- Tools used: GitHub CLI, Wrangler, Notion API, Whisper API, Nano Banana Pro (image generation)
- Agent skills active: github, notion, nano-banana-pro, openai-whisper-api, weather, discord

---

## What We Learned

1. The best hackathon ideas come from pivots. The Merit System idea died; AI Jobs Finder was born.
2. An AI agent reading docs written by another AI agent, then triggering a workflow autonomously — that's not a demo. That's the product working exactly as intended.
3. Leveraging an SDK properly matters more than having it installed. The difference between `package.json` and `import { Agent }` is the difference between optics and substance.
4. Documentation is infrastructure. The `AGENTS.md` and `skill.md` files weren't afterthoughts — they were what made the "another agent triggered it" moment possible.

